 rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Ingrum","meanings":["English: variant of   Ingram  ."]},{"name":"Ingraham","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Ingram  , influenced by   Graham  . This name is now more common in the US than in Britain."]},{"name":"Engram","meanings":["English: variant of   Ingram  . This form, recorded inthe 13th century, now appears to have died out in the British Isles."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Roger Ingram was born about 1240, in Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales. He married Mrs Roger Ingram before 1270, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1240–Deceased":"umbes 1240–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","about 1240":"umbes 1240","Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1240–Deceased":"noin 1240–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","about 1240":"noin 1240","Denbigh,